"Shongwe M.E., Graversen R.G., van Oldenborgh G.J., van den Hurk B.J.J.M., Doblas-Reyes F.J.","Energy budget of the extreme Autumn 2006 in Europe",2011,"Climate Dynamics","36","5-6",,"1055","1066",,,10.1007/s00382-009-0689-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952250383&partnerID=40&md5=c550c3defb26d6ad840d073a002904d1","Koninklijk Nederlands Meteorologisch Instituut (KNMI), P. O. Box 201, 3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasting (ECMWF), Reading, United Kingdom","Shongwe, M.E., Koninklijk Nederlands Meteorologisch Instituut (KNMI), P. O. Box 201, 3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; Graversen, R.G., Koninklijk Nederlands Meteorologisch Instituut (KNMI), P. O. Box 201, 3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; van Oldenborgh, G.J., Koninklijk Nederlands Meteorologisch Instituut (KNMI), P. O. Box 201, 3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; van den Hurk, B.J.J.M., Koninklijk Nederlands Meteorologisch Instituut (KNMI), P. O. Box 201, 3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; Doblas-Reyes, F.J., European Centre for Medium Range Weather Forecasting (ECMWF), Reading, United Kingdom","Autumn 2006 was extraordinarily mild in many parts of Europe. Near-surface temperatures were more than three standard deviations above the 1961-1990 climatology. Even accounting for global warming, this event was far outside the probability density function of previous observations or climate model simulations. To investigate the mechanisms behind this event, the energy-budget for Autumn 2006 in Europe is estimated. Atmospheric energy-transport convergence over Europe is calculated and compared with the net energy flux at the top of the atmosphere as well as at the earth's surface. The central North-Atlantic Ocean constituted the major source of energy. Here, the release of both sensible and latent heat was anomalously high. Atmospheric circulation played a crucial role by transporting the excess energy into Europe. Of this energy excess, dry-static energy was larger than the latent part, partly due to an additional contribution derived from a conversion of latent energy to sensible heat, which occurred upstream of the study area in the eastern Atlantic. In Europe, surface turbulent-energy fluxes into the atmosphere respond to atmospheric energy-transport convergence and are accordingly suppressed due to the anomalously high temperature and humidity content of the overlying air. The net outflow of radiational energy to space is anomalously high but not sufficient to offset the large positive anomaly of energy found over Europe. Even though the relative humidity was near its normal values in Europe, the specific humidity was considerably higher than usual. The high water-vapour content induced a local radiative positive feedback, increasing the opacity of the atmosphere to long-wave radiation. This appears to have significantly contributed to the extreme event. Atmospheric circulation played a crucial role in sustaining this feedback loop. © 2009 Springer-Verlag.","Atmospheric energy budget; Atmospheric energy transport; Autumn 2006 temperature anomaly; Extreme event; Long-wave radiative feedback","atmospheric circulation; autumn; climate feedback; climate modeling; climatology; energy budget; energy flux; extreme event; global warming; latent heat flux; sensible heat flux; surface temperature; temperature anomaly; water vapor; Europe",,,,,,"Alexander, L.V., Zhang, X., Peterson, T.C., Caesar, J., Gleason, B., Tank, A.M.G.K., Haylock, M., Vazquez-Aguirre, J.L., Global observed changes in daily climate extremes of temperature and precipitation (2006) J Geophys Res, 111, pp. D05109. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006290; Beniston, M., The 2003 heat wave in Europe: a shape of things to come? An analysis based on swiss climatological data and model simulations (2004) Geophys Res Lett, p. 31. , doi: 10. 1029/2003GL018857; Beniston, M., Stephenson, D.B., Christensen, O.B., Ferro, C.A.T., Frei, C., Goyette, S., Halsnaes, K., Woth, K., Future extreme events in European climate: an exploration of regional climate model projections (2007) Clim Change, 81, pp. 71-95. , doi:10.1007/s10584-006-9226-z; Cattiaux, J., Vautard, R., Yiou, P., Origins of the extremely warm European fall in 2006 (2009) Geophys Res Lett, p. 36. , doi: 10. 1029/2009GL037339; Ciais, P., Reichstein, M., Viovy, N., Granier, A., Ogée, J., Allard, V., Aubinet, M., Valentini, R., Europe-wide reduction in primary productivity caused by the heat and drought in 2003 (2005) Nature, 437, pp. 529-533. , doi:10.1038/nature03972; Ferranti, L., Viterbo, P., The European summer of 2003: sensitivity to soil water initial conditions (2006) J Clim, 19, pp. 3659-3680; Fischer, E.M., Seneviratne, S.I., Lüthi, D., Schär, C., Contribution of land-atmosphere coupling to recent European summer heat waves (2007) Geophys Res Lett, 34, pp. L06+707; Graversen, R.G., Do changes in the midlatitude circulation have any impact on the Arctic surface air temperature trend? (2006) J Clim, 19, pp. 5422-5438; Graversen, R.G., Källén, E., Tjernström, M., Körnich, H., Atmospheric mass-transport inconsistencies in the ERA-40 reanalysis (2007) Q J R Meteorol Soc, 133, pp. 673-680; Hallegatte, S., Lahellec, A., Grandpeix, J.Y., An elicitation of the dynamic nature of water vapor feedback in climate change using a 1D model (2006) J Atmos Sci, 63, pp. 1878-1894; Kanamitsu, M., Ebisuzaki, W., Woollen, J., Yang, S.K., Hnilo, J.J., Fiorino, M., Potter, G.L., NCEP-DEO AMIP-II reanalysis (R-2) (2002) Bull Am Meterol Soc, 83, pp. 1631-1643; Kiehl, J.T., Trenberth, K.E., Earth's annual global mean energy budget (1997) Bull Am Meteorol Soc, 78, pp. 197-208; Klein Tank, A.M.G., Können, G.P., Trends in indices of daily temperature and precipitation extremes in Europe, 1946-1999 (2003) J Clim, 16, pp. 3665-3680; Klein Tank, A.M.G., Peterson, T.C., Quadir, D.A., Dorji, S., Zou, X., Tang, H., Santhosh, K., Spektorman, T., Changes in daily temperature and precipitation extremes in central and south Asia